article.headline: SE Missouri State 84, Jacksonville St. 65
article.story: CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) -- Terrick Willoughby scored a career-high 25 points and keyed a second-half run that erased a 10-point deficit, helping Southeast Missouri State beat Jacksonville State 84-65 on Thursday night. Dainmon Gonner had 18 of his 24 points in the first half for the Redhawks (8-10, 3-4 Ohio Valley), and he added nine rebounds. Southeast Missouri shot 65 percent in the second half and 56 percent overall. Brandon Davis scored 20 points for Jacksonville State (4-15, 0-7), which has lost 13 in a row. The Gamecocks were 7-for-14 from 3-point range, but just 1-for-6 in the second half. Willoughby and Reggie Golson had nine points apiece in a 25-6 run that put Southeast Missouri ahead 64-55 with 7:41 to go. Jacksonville State got no closer than seven points the rest of the way. Willoughby's previous career high was 17 points Dec. 22 at North Texas. Davis' 3-pointer with three seconds to go in the first half gave Jacksonville State a 43-39 lead, and the Gamecocks scored the first six points after the break for a 49-39 lead with 17:16 left. Jacksonville State hasn't won since Nov. 23, its longest slump in nine seasons of Division I competition. Golson added 12 points and nine rebounds for the Redhawks. Carlos Lumpkin and Anthony Wilson had 12 points apiece for Jacksonville State, and Walker Russell added 11 points and nine assists.
